description:
We are excited that Bottom Line’s Resume Workshop is next week Thurs Oct 20 at 4:30pm!

This is confirmation we got your RSVP for the event!

We hope you are just as excited as we are to dig deep into resume best practices and get an individualized resume review from one of our professional volunteers!


As a reminder, the event will start at 4:30pm EST/3:30 CST via Zoom. You will receive a Zoom link the morning of the event.


We are asking everyone attending to please complete basic resume formatting edits before the event. We recommend using this resume format for a clean and easy to edit resume: https://bit.ly/2XfbVRQ Can't wait to see you! Email any questions to careerny@bottomline.org.<mailto:careerny@bottomline.org>


PLEASE NOTE: When saving your resume, please save it as a Word document or Google doc and NOT as a PDF document. This will make it easier for our volunteers to review and add comments to your resume.


Finally, everyone who attends the entire event will receive a $15 gift card following the event!


We will be in touch next week with a Zoom link. Please reach out to careerny@bottomline.org<mailto:careerny@bottomline.org> with any questions or concerns, or if you are no longer able to make it to the event. See you next week!

Finding New Ways of Thinking and Coping with Academic StressIs it a challenge to manage competing academic demands* while staying on top of assignments* Falling behind academically can lead to increased stress and can cause problems in multiple areas of one*s life* This 45 minute workshop is designed to help you approach your academic demands differently by discovering new pathways of thinking* You will be encouraged to challenge unhelpful thoughts and re-frame your thinking* which can often lend to productive outcomes* including increased focus and heightened academic success*

Join us on our second google hangout session all about Student life at Tandon : Students will discuss how their life is like at NYU Tandon, including their dorm or commute life, dining hall plans, weekly schedules, and weekend life.

Do you find it difficult to make friends* focus on academics or feel confident in social situations* Join us for a cognitive behavior therapy informed workshop designed to help you to better understand how your thoughts can impact your feelings and behaviors* Learn skills to reduce excessive thinking* social anxiety and stress related to academic performance and social interactions* This workshop is designed for undergraduate students who wish to better manage their anxiety and stress levels*

description:
Join our speaker Will Lifferth for an introduction to two powerful Google Cloud tools.

Storing and querying massive datasets can be time consuming and expensive without the right hardware and infrastructure. BigQuery is an enterprise data warehouse that solves this problem by enabling super-fast SQL queries using the processing power of Google's infrastructure. Simply move your data into BigQuery and let us handle the hard work. You can control access to both the project and your data based on your business needs, such as giving others the ability to view or query your data.

You can access BigQuery in the Console, the Web UI or a command-line tool, or by making calls to the BigQuery REST API using a variety of client libraries such as Java, .NET, or Python. There are also a variety of third-party tools that you can use to interact with BigQuery, such as visualizing the data or loading the data.

This hands-on lab shows you how to use the Web UI to query public tables and load sample data into BigQuery.

Attendees will receive $25 in Google Cloud credits to explore the Cloud Console.

Register and receive a direct invite to the Live Google Meet with chat feature.

Welcome to the Amazon BEN Tech Coding Interview Best Practices! 

The sessions meet on Wednesdays.  You will automatically be registered for all sessions.  You are welcome to attend as few or as many sessions as you like.  Please start by entering your name and email address ahead of the session.

**What Is Amazon BEN Tech Interview Prep (BTIP)?**

Amazon's Affinity subgroup BTIP is focused on the recruitment and retention of underrepresented engineers for the Tech industry as a whole.

**What can I expect from the Coding Interview Best Practices?**

You will have the opportunity to participate in an hour-long coding interview prep session. The objective of this session is to equip you with valuable insights to ready yourself for a technical interview. Additionally, you will get to interact with alumni from the BTIP program and learn from their interview experiences through their shared tips.

Details:
- We will be using GoToWebinar.  You can install this before the session here: https://global.gotomeeting.com/install
- You can join our session by using a Mac, PC, or a mobile device.

Agenda:
- Welcome and introductions
- What to expect in an interview
- Interview best practices
- Interview question demonstration
- Q & A

Here is a link to help you with the Software Development Interviews
https://www.amazon.jobs/en/landing_pages/software-development-topics 

Still more questions? Here is our FAQ page!
https://www.amazon.jobs/en/faqs

Join from a PC, Mac, iPad, iPhone or Android device:
    Please click this URL to join. https://acm-org.zoom.us/w/91698483070?tk=KZvKwM6S7KsnB_Br7_qG7F-VcPhLqPZ2qI1S5vTP87g.DQMAAAAVWafPfhZBNmZVUUhTU1RiR2RhenlJYmNpSHpBAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA&uuid=WN_-KiH9D2LTZWT0pXdzl9Fug
Description: In this TechTalk, we will explore the challenges and best practices for developing ethical and responsible Large Language Models (LLMs). The talk will delve into the importance of transparency and explainability, showcasing methods such as attention visualization and model distillation that provide critical insights into model behavior. We will address the control of generated content through techniques including reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF), token penalization, external moderation systems, and prompt engineering. Finally, we will tackle the issue of bias mitigation, emphasizing the need for transparency in the pre-training data used for these billion-parameter models, diverse and representative data, as well as pre-, in-, and post-processing techniques to ensure fairness in LLMs.

These considerations have taken on heightened significance in light of the recently proposed EU AI Act, the first major regulatory framework for AI. Although the Act originates in Europe, its reach is globally impacting organizations that interact with European entities or serve European customers. In addition, it might set a precedent that could inspire similar legislation in other regions, thereby broadening its implications.

Moreover, understanding these critical aspects of responsible AI not only aids in the creation of LLMs that are ethical and safe for real-world applications but also accelerates the development process for downstream tasks. Since these techniques can be used as an aid for developers to swiftly identify and correct issues, improving model performance and reliability.

Event Name: Hack.Diversity Fellowship Interviews
Event Description: Thank you for your interest in the 2024 Hack.Diversity Fellowship! We’re excited to learn more about you and your technical skills in your upcoming interview. The interview will consist of one live 30-minute technical discussion with a Hack.Community member. There is no formal coding assessment. Instead, there will be a technical discussion. Please be prepared to talk about your technical experience, projects, and passions!After selecting your interview time, you will receive:
One email confirming your interview.
One email with interview preparation resources.
We're so excited to meet with you! If you have any questions, please reach out to Claire Joy Moss at cmoss@hackdiversity.com. See you soon!
Date & Time: 03:30pm - 04:00pm (Eastern Time - US & Canada) on Monday, October 2, 2023
Location: https://us02web.zoom.us/j/87929262473

Please choose the track you are interviewing for.: NYC Software Engineering

Have you completed your video interview?: No

Cancellation Policy: Hack.Diversity is eager to fill our 2024 Cohort with those who align with our mission of breaking down barriers for Black/Latinx professionals in tech. If you are unable to commit to our mission and program, feel free to cancel your interview.

Need to make changes to this event?

Reschedule: https://calendly.com/reschedulings/4eed4d99-f067-45eb-a561-744426ddc5fd

Please see G-SWEP onsite kickoff event details below:
  • When: Friday, Oct 6, 2023 at 9 am - 4 pm EST
  • Where: 111 8th Ave, New York, NY 10011
  • Enter through the 8th Ave lobby between 15th & 16th St.
Here are a few things you need to ensure you’re ready:
  • Bring your laptop for coding during problem sessions on 10/6. Otherwise you will be provided pencil / paper for coding.
  • Please arrive on-time / early between 9 - 9:30 am. 
  • We kindly ask that you provide us with at least a 24-hour notice, if you are unable to attend and need to cancel. No-shows or day-of-event cancellations may impact your ability to attend Basta events/ programming in the future. Hi there!

Please see below the details of your weekly virtual G-SWEP (Google Software Engineer Program) sessions with a Basta mentee.

[ACTION REQUIRED] SWEs, please update this calendar invite with YOUR Google Meet link prior to your 1st scheduled session.

MATERIALS, for SWEs:

  • Attendance Form [only for SWEs to complete at the top of every weekly meeting]

  • Google Drive folder with mentee's Google doc for coding problems and solutions [SWEs, click on your hyperlinked name here to access your dedicated folder]

  • go/gswep

1:1 VIRTUAL SESSION GUIDANCE, for SWEs:

  • Refer to the email titled "[Action Required] Fall '23 G-SWEP: Weekly Virtual Mentorship Sessions!" for mentee specific details.

  • Please begin every meeting with a shared Google document for presenting problems and coding solutions.

  • As a reminder, you will be given ownership of the calendar invite for your weekly 1:1 sessions so that you can add/update your Google Meet information and also maintain management of the invite between you and your assigned participant.  

  • Please see the G-SWEP SWE Volunteer Expectation Guide for additional information on conducting a session and working with students. 

AFTER YOUR FIRST or SECOND MEETING, SWEs:

  • Please fill out go/gswep-fellow-assessment.

  • Coordinate directly with your mentee to shift to a mutually convenient time to meet each week, if needed.
